33 North Partners focuses on providing resources to help early stage companies achieve success. The founders of 33 North Partners have extensive experience with early stage companies, and have been operators, investors, and board members, with multiple successful exits between them. They are not simply consultants, but through launching their own companies have directly experienced the successes and pitfalls of building a going concern.Ms. Holmes founded 33 North Partners on the principal that young technology companies often don’t have access to experienced advisors or mentors who have successfully started and exited a company, or direct access to capital sources. Ms. Holmes brings her strong ability to distill a strategic vision for young companies and her broad range of marketing experience to 33 North Partners. In combination with her co-founders, 33 North Partners solves these issues by guiding companies through areas such as their exit strategy, fundable company strategy, and capitalization strategy.  She brings a unique combination of creativity and experience to this role that is highly effective in helping early companies to becoming going concerns, and has personally engaged in raising over $3m in private capital for her partner companies.

The MIT Enterprise Forum is a global organization in 27 cities.  In all cases, it is focused on accelerating the growth of the local entrepreneurial community.  Although it is an MIT organization, it requires no specific university affiliation for participation in any of its programs.For MIT Enterprise Forum Phoenix, Ms. Holmes brings 10 years of Internet marketing and expertise in developing and overseeing implementation of the marketing strategy. Ms. Holmes has been instrumental in conceptualization, strategy, and implementation for the MIT EF—including instituting capital formation programs, educational outreach, and community building programs such as the Great Arizona Code Challenge. She has created an impressive Forum with world-class speakers from institutions such as MIT’s Computer Science and AI Laboratory, and Harvard’s Department of Physics and Applied Sciences, and has been hand selected by MIT EF Global as Co-Chair of the Global Strategy Committee.

Startup Weekend (http://startupweekend.org) is a global challenge that takes place in cities all over the world— where entrepreneurs come together and turn an idea for a company into reality in 54 hours.  These events tend to be very tech innovation focused, and provide a place for entrepenreurs to meet co-founders, mentors, and gain momentum for their ideas.  The education, connections, mentors, and resources available to entrepreneurs at Startup Weekend is unparalleled, and the Phoenix team strived to make this event as impactful and uplifting for our community as possible.  Pat Sullivan, founder of ACT and Cantatta honored us by kicking the weekend off with a moving speech, and the caliber of mentors, judges, and volunteers couldn't have been higher.  Several incredible companies were formed, the weekend was wrapped up with company pitches that were intelligent, polished, and inspiring— and that caught the attention of investors in the audience and the judging panel.  It was truly an honor to be such a large part of coordinating an event like this.  From raising sponsorship dollars and over $18,400 in in-kind prizes, to marketing and budgeting, to securing judges and mentors, and mentoring many the groups myself over the weekend, I enjoyed every moment.

summary: Ms. Holmes has two principal roles: Founding Principal of Startups Reimagined, and Executive Director for the MIT Enterprise Forum Phoenix. Both reflect her passion in supporting the development of early stage technology companies. She is a key influencer in the Arizona startup landscape, although her consulting engagements extend nationally.Ms. Holmes founded Startups Reimagined on the principal that young technology companies need much more “hands on” support than traditional advisory services provide. Technology companies often need the support of an infrastructure of services to turn their concept into a going, funded concern. Startups Reimagined, through its network of senior resources is able to support those young companies through their formative stages.For MIT Enterprise Forum Phoenix, she brings 10 years of internet marketing and expertise in developing and overseeing implementation of the marketing strategy. Ms. Holmes has been instrumental in conceptualization, strategy, and implementation for the MIT EF—including important programs such as the Great Arizona Code Challenge and a statewide festival celebrating technology. She has created an impressive calendar of events with world class speakers from institutions such as MIT’s Computer Science and AI Laboratory, and Harvard’s Department of Physics and Applied Sciences.Ms. Holmes is also Founding Principal at Communications Reimagined—a firm dedicated to providing marketing strategy and implementation, leveraging today’s latest communications channels including the web and social media, and also utilizing traditional, but effective methods such as events, PR, and traditional media advertising. Ms. Holmes has served as a media and internet marketing consultant to a variety of companies and has regularly been featured as spokesperson for various companies. She volunteers as chair of Kaufman Foundation’s 1 Million Cups Phoenix and Techstar’s Startup Weekend.
